        </trans-unit>
        <trans-unit id="103" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve">
          <source>You can customize the appearance of any cell by handling the <ph id="ph1">&lt;xref:System.Windows.Forms.DataGridView&gt;</ph> control's <ph id="ph2">&lt;xref:System.Windows.Forms.DataGridView.CellPainting&gt;</ph> event.</source>
        </trans-unit>
        <trans-unit id="104" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve">
          <source>You can extract the <ph id="ph1">&lt;xref:System.Windows.Forms.DataGridView&gt;</ph> control's <ph id="ph2">&lt;xref:System.Drawing.Graphics&gt;</ph> from the <ph id="ph3">&lt;xref:System.Windows.Forms.DataGridViewCellPaintingEventArgs.Graphics%2A&gt;</ph> property of the <ph id="ph4">&lt;xref:System.Windows.Forms.DataGridViewCellPaintingEventArgs&gt;</ph>.</source>
        </trans-unit>
        <trans-unit id="105" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve">
          <source>With this <ph id="ph1">&lt;xref:System.Drawing.Graphics&gt;</ph>, you can affect the appearance of the entire <ph id="ph2">&lt;xref:System.Windows.Forms.DataGridView&gt;</ph> control, but you will usually want to affect only the appearance of the cell that is currently being painted.</source>
        </trans-unit>
        <trans-unit id="106" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve">
          <source>The <ph id="ph1">&lt;xref:System.Windows.Forms.DataGridViewCellPaintingEventArgs.ClipBounds%2A&gt;</ph> property of the <ph id="ph2">&lt;xref:System.Windows.Forms.DataGridViewCellPaintingEventArgs&gt;</ph> enables you to restrict your painting operations to the cell that is currently being painted.</source>
        </trans-unit>
        <trans-unit id="107" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve">
          <source>In the following code example, you will paint all the cells in a <ph id="ph1">`ContactName`</ph> column using the <ph id="ph2">&lt;xref:System.Windows.Forms.DataGridView&gt;</ph> control's color scheme.</source>
        </trans-unit>
        <trans-unit id="108" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve">
          <source>Each cell's text content is painted in <ph id="ph1">&lt;xref:System.Drawing.Color.Crimson%2A&gt;</ph>, and an inset rectangle is drawn in the same color as the <ph id="ph2">&lt;xref:System.Windows.Forms.DataGridView&gt;</ph> control's <ph id="ph3">&lt;xref:System.Windows.Forms.DataGridView.GridColor%2A&gt;</ph> property.</source>
